  "prompt": "Why did Ian Mckellen have emotional breakdowns when on set on the Hobbit?",
  "response": "Ian McKellen experienced emotional challenges while filming \"The Hobbit\" primarily due to the extensive use of green screen technology. In his role as Gandalf, many scenes required him to perform alone against a green screen, with the other characters added digitally in post-production. This was a significant change from \"The Lord of the Rings\" trilogy, where McKellen had the opportunity to interact with fellow actors on set, creating a more immersive and traditional acting experience.\n\nDuring one particularly overwhelming moment, McKellen reportedly broke down and expressed frustration, feeling isolated and distanced from the other cast members due to the technical demands of the production. He is quoted as saying, \"This is not why I became an actor.\" However, it's important to note that McKellen continued to approach his work professionally and remained committed to his role, ultimately completing the film series. The situation highlights the emotional and psychological challenges actors can face when working in heavily CGI-dependent environments.",
